{{Hinduism_small}}
'''Yogi Swatmarama''' ({{lang-sa|स्वात्माराम}}; [[IAST]]: svātmārāma) was a 15th and 16th century [[Yoga|yogic]] sage in [[India]]. He is best known for compiling the yoga manual [[Hatha Yoga Pradipika|Hatha Pradipika]] or ''Light on Hatha Yoga''. This manual describes the use of [[Shatkarma]], [[Asanas]], [[Pranayama]], [[Mudras]], and [[Bandha (Yoga)|Bandhas]], and their practice as the means to awaken the [[Kundalini]], leading to deeper and deeper states of [[Samadhi]]. Swatmarama maitains throughout the text that [[Hatha Yoga]]'s true purpose is the arousal of the Kundalini, until perfection in [[Raja Yoga]] is achieved, i.e. liberation.<ref>http://www.bodhitree.com/lectures/Georg_Feuerstein_Yoga_Tradition_interview_by_Richard_Miller.html</ref><ref> Hatha Yoga Pradipika, e-book translated by Pancham Sinh, www.sacredtexts.com </ref>

Very little is known about the actual Swatmarama, but the fourth line of the text attributes its lineage to the [[Nath|Nath Sampraday]]:
:"Matsyendra, Goraksa, etc., knew Hatha Vidyā, and by their favour Yogī Swātmārāma also learnt it from them."<ref> Hatha Yoga Pradipika, e-book translated by Pancham Sinh, www.sacredtexts.com </ref>
